         <abstract id="aspace_aa07a76fd76edf15afb39aa80d8311ff">Correspondence and miscellaneous papers of the New England Council Steel Committee, formed to work for the construction of a steel mill in New England. The collection also includes addresses, reports, memoranda, press releases, and printed matter of the New England Council and the New England Steel Development Corporation.</abstract>
         <origination label="Creator">
            <corpname source="local">
               <part localtype="agent_corporate_entity">New England Council Steel Committee</part>
            </corpname>
         </origination>
      </did>
      <acqinfo id="aspace_e67d468fd3ceca49f1c2198172a7fea9">
         <head>Immediate Source of Acquisition</head>
         <p>Gift in 1951 of Frederick S. Blackall, Jr., and of Edward Ingraham; further papers were transferred to this collection from Sterling Memorial Library in 1981.</p>
      </acqinfo>
      <accessrestrict id="aspace_dae703316678bc1bbff524aceaf79ebf">
         <head>Conditions Governing Access</head>
         <p>The materials are open for research.</p>
      </accessrestrict>
      <prefercite id="aspace_ae454c1a20582912e822c784a2ff9262">
         <head>Preferred Citation</head>
         <p>New England Council Steel Committee Records. Manuscripts and Archives, Yale University Library.</p>
      </prefercite>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_339832dc90863aa51c908f67ce6372ac">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The New England Council, founded in 1925, is an association of the six New England states (Connecticut, Maine, Massachusetts, New Hampshire, Rhode Island, and Vermont), dedicated to developing and maintaining comprehensive views of economic and social problems and conditions common to the New England states, and to promoting cooperative solutions to these problems. It emphasizes research and the dissemination of information.</p>
         <p>In 1947 the Council proposed that a steel mill be built in New England; this collection contains correspondence, memoranda, reports, printed matter, and so forth assembled to promote this project. Included are papers of both the New England Council Steel Committee and the New England Steel Development Corporation, which was set up in 1950 to research and then construct the proposed steel plant. There is also some other general printed matter relating to the New England Council.</p>
         <p>The papers were the gift in 1951 of Frederick S. Blackall, Jr., chairman of the New England Council Iron and Steel Supply Committee, and of Edward Ingraham.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      <bioghist id="aspace_f7504ace68727b62425b02d00451017c">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>The New England Council was founded in 1925 as an association of the six New England states dedicated to developing and maintaining comprehensive views of economic and social problems and conditions common to those states, and to promoting cooperative solutions to these problems.</p>
      </bioghist>
